'''George Theodore Felbeck''' (February 1, 1897 - March 1, 1962) was an American businessman who was born in [[Salina, Kansas]], United States to Lewis and Matilda Felbeck.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:S3HT-6L82-QM?cc=1325221&wc=9B7D-3YX%3A1030552401%2C1030995401%2C1033896901|title=United States Census, 1900|publisher=National Archives and Records Administration}}</ref> He married Helen Mildred née Kniseley on November 5, 1919.<ref name="alumni-quarterly-1919">{{cite news | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HGDnAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA132#v=onepage&q=felbeck&f=false | title = The Alumni Quarterly and Fortnightly Notes, Volumes 5-7 | accessdate = 2012-11-29 }}</ref>
He was a graduate of the [[University of Illinois]] where he received his B.S.M.E. degree in 1919 and his M.S.M.E. degree in 1921. He left college in 1918 to serve in the infantry of the [[U.S. Army]]. While at Illinois he was a member of [[Sigma Pi]] fraternity. He received his Ph.D. in [[physical chemistry]] from the [[California Institute of Technology]] in 1943.<ref name = Emerald1962>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|date=Spring 1962|volume=49|number=1|magazine=The Emerald of Sigma Pi|title=Adytum on High|page=40|url=http://www.enivation.com/SigmaPi/Archive/Emerald/1962/SP_EMERALD_VOL_49_NO_1_SPRING_1962.pdf}}</ref>
He became a research assistant for [[Union Carbide]] in 1923, then headed its plant in [[Buffalo, New York]]. He then moved to [[New York City]] in 1925 to serve as an engineer for Union Carbide. He served at [[Oak Ridge, Tennessee]] from 1942 to 1946 in the [[Manhattan Project]] as a chemical and nuclear engineer, under the command of [[Kenneth Nichols]]. In 1944 he was appointed president of Union Carbide and served until he retired in February 1962.<ref name = Emerald1962/>
He and Helen had four children, Dr. George T. Felbeck, Jr., Dr. David K. Felbeck, Richard B. Felbeck, and Karen H. Canaday.<ref name = Emerald1962/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:3QSQ-G9MT-6WWN?cc=2000219&wc=QZX5-32Q%3A790105301%2C796133301%2C798689901%2C952658801|title="United States Census, 1940|publisher=National Archives and Records Administration}}</ref>
Felbeck was one of 95 passengers who died on the [[American Airlines Flight 1]] crash on March 1, 1962.<ref name="review-1962-3-2b">{{cite news | title = Noted Men Lose Lives In Crash | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uqQRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FegDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6322,563321 | format = PDF | agency = AP | newspaper = The Spokesman-Review | location = Spokane, WA | date = March 2, 1962 | page = 1 | accessdate = 2009-11-22 }} ([http://theflightpath.wordpress.com/2009/11/17/noted-men-lose-lives-in-crash/ plaintext])</ref>
